## .NET 8 Migration: `EventProcessor`

### Critical Issues in the Original Code

| Issue | Severity | Details |
|-------|----------|---------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | 🔴 **Breaks** | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 5+ |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | 🟡 Won't wake `ManualResetEvent.WaitOne()` | It only interrupts *managed* blocking calls like `Thread.Sleep`, `Monitor.Wait` — **not** `WaitOne()` on a `WaitHandle` |
| Race condition | 🟡 Bug | Multiple `Enqueue` calls can fire before `Dequeue` runs — but `Reset()` clears the signal, so only **one** item is dequeued per wake cycle, silently losing items |
| No cancellation | 🟡 Design | No cooperative shutdown; the `while(true)` loop has no exit path |

### Migrated Code (.NET 8)

Replace the entire manual synchronization stack with `Channel<T>`, which is purpose-built for async producer/consumer:

```csharp
using System.Threading.Channels;

public class EventProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Task? _workerTask;

    public void Start()
    {
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken ct)
    {
        // ReadAllAsync drains every item — no lost-signal race condition.
        await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(ct))
        {
            Handle(item);
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        if (!_channel.Writer.TryWrite(item))
            throw new InvalidOperationException("Channel is closed.");
    }

    public async ValueTask StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        _channel.Writer.Complete();           // signal no more items
        _cts.CancelAfter(timeout ?? TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5)); // hard deadline

        if (_workerTask is not null)
        {
            try { await _workerTask; }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) { /* expected on timeout */ }
        }
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        await StopAsync();
        _cts.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* your logic */ }
}
```

### What Changed and Why

```
ManualResetEvent + Queue + lock  →  Channel<string>
  Eliminates the lost-signal race. Channel is thread-safe and
  backpressure-aware; no manual locking needed.

Thread                           →  Task.Run
  Uses the thread pool instead of a dedicated thread.
  If you need a long-lived dedicated thread, pass
  TaskCreationOptions.LongRunning.

Thread.Abort() / Interrupt()     →  CancellationToken + Channel.Complete()
  Cooperative cancellation. Complete() tells the reader the
  stream is finished; CancellationToken enforces a hard timeout.

while(true) + WaitOne            →  await foreach (ReadAllAsync)
  Drains ALL queued items, yields when empty, exits cleanly
  when the channel completes or the token fires.
```

### Pitfalls to Watch For

1. **`Thread.Abort` is gone** — any code calling it will throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` at runtime, not compile time. Search your codebase: `grep -r "\.Abort()" --include="*.cs"`.

2. **`Handle()` exceptions** — in the original code an exception kills the thread silently. In the migrated code it surfaces on `await _workerTask`. Add a `try/catch` inside the loop if you want to keep processing after a failure.

3. **Sync callers** — if your call site can't `await StopAsync()`, use `StopAsync().AsTask().GetAwaiter().GetResult()` as a last resort, but prefer propagating `async` up the stack.

4. **Unbounded channel** — `CreateUnbounded` has no backpressure. If producers can outrun the consumer, switch to `CreateBounded<string>(capacity)` and use `await _channel.Writer.WriteAsync(item)`.
